{"title_page": "Palpatine", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{short description|Villain in Star Wars}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Darth Sidious<br />{{small|Sheev Palpatine}}\n| image              = Emperor RotJ.png\n| caption            = Ian McDiarmid as Palpatine in<br>''[[Return of the Jedi]]'' (1983)\n| series             = [[Star Wars]]\n| first              = ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'' (1980)\n| creator            = [[George Lucas]]\n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Dark Lord of the [[Sith]]\n* [[Senator]] from [[Naboo]]\n* [[Supreme Chancellor]] of the [[Galactic Republic]]\n* [[Emperor]] of the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]]\n}}\n| species            = [[Human]]\n| gender             = Male\n| affiliation        = {{Unbulleted list|[[Sith|Sith Order]]|Galactic Republic|Confederacy of Independent Systems|Galactic Empire|[[First Order (Star Wars)|First Order]]|[[Final Order]]|Sith Eternal}}\n| family             = Unnamed Palpatine (son){{efn|name=boba|[[The Rise of Skywalker#Tie-in literature and merchandise|The novelization of ''The Rise of Skywalker'']] reveals that Palpatine's 'son' was a failed [[Human cloning|clone]] of himself.<ref>{{cite web |last=Agar |first=Chris |title=''Star Wars'' Confirms Rey's Father Is A Failed Palpatine Clone |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-rise-skywalker-rey-father-palpatine-clone/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet Inc. |accessdate=March 4, 2020 |date=March 4, 2020}}</ref>}}<br>[[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]] (granddaughter)\n| portrayer          = {{Unbulleted list|[[Ian McDiarmid]] (''Episodes I\u2013III'', ''V'',{{efn|2004 DVD and subsequent releases of ''Episode V''}} ''VI'', ''IX'')|[[Marjorie Eaton]] (original release of ''Episode V''; visual)<ref name=\"earwolf1\">{{cite web|last=Gourley|first=Matt|title=I Was There Too|url=http://www.earwolf.com/episode/bonus-episode-the-empire-strikes-back-controversy-averted/|website=earwolf.com|publisher=Earwolf|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Hidalgo twitter\">{{cite tweet |user=pablohidalgo |number=791503521925304320 |date= October 26, 2016 |title=Okay here's what I've got. It is not Elaine Baker in the movie. @PhilTippett sculpted the piece and Rick applied it. }}</ref>}}\n| voice              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Clive Revill]] (original release of ''Episode V'')\n* Ian McDiarmid (''[[Star Wars Rebels|Rebels]]'', Season 2 since 2019, Season 4)\n* [[Sam Witwer]] (''Rebels'', Season 2 until 2019)\n* [[Ian Abercrombie]] (''The Clone Wars'' [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|film]] and [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|TV series]], Seasons 1\u20136)\n* [[Tim Curry]] (''The Clone Wars'', Seasons 5\u20136)\n* [[Nick Jameson]] (''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|Clone Wars]]'')\n}}\n| franchise          = ''[[Star Wars]]''\n| alt                = \n| first_major        = \n| first_minor        = \n| first_issue        = \n| first_date         = \n| last_major         = \n| last_minor         = \n| last_issue         = \n| last_date          = \n| firstgame          = ''[[Super Star Wars: Return of the Jedi]]'' (1994)\n| last               = ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker|The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (2019)\n| based_on           = \n| adapted_by         = \n| full_name          = Sheev Palpatine\n| alias              = The Emperor\n| origin             = \n| lbl21              = Homeworld\n| data21             = Naboo\n| religion           = Sith Order\n}}\n\n'''Darth Sidious'''{{efn|The character's first name was developed for the shelved ''[[Star Wars: Underworld]]'' television series, but was first announced in the novel ''[[Star Wars: Tarkin|Tarkin]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lussier |first=Germain |title=Here's the Real Deal With That Leaked Star Wars Footage |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/heres-the-real-deal-with-that-leaked-star-wars-footage-1841389155 |website=io9 |accessdate=February 4, 2020 |language=en-us |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Star Wars Underworld: Putting the Pieces Together |url=https://docs.google.com/document/d/1DdxDngZpm6acDGOjXTmj6YeFSMO9aI2fNnAc1lL5HOY/edit |website=Google Docs |accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Tarkin book\"/>}} is a fictional character<!--Do not use the term \"antagonist\", \"villain\", or related terms as per WP:Manual of Style/Film--> in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' franchise created by [[George Lucas]]. Initially credited as '''The Emperor''' in ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'' (1980), Sidious is also known by his public identity as '''Palpatine'''. He is mainly portrayed by [[Ian McDiarmid]].\n\nDarth Sidious appears in each trilogy in the nine-film [[Skywalker saga]]. In the [[Star Wars Trilogy|original trilogy]], he is depicted as emperor of the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]] and the master of [[Darth Vader]]. In the [[Star Wars prequel trilogy|prequel trilogy]], he is portrayed as a charismatic politician who uses [[Machiavellianism (politics)|Machiavellian]] manipulation to transform the [[Galactic Republic]] into the Empire, and turn [[Jedi|Jedi Knight]] Anakin Skywalker to the dark side of [[the Force]]. In ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker|The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (2019), the final film in the [[Star Wars sequel trilogy|sequel trilogy]], Sidious is revealed to be the mastermind behind the [[First Order (Star Wars)|First Order]] and its former leader, [[Supreme Leader Snoke|Snoke]], as well as the grandfather of [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]], the last Jedi.\n\nSince the release of ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'' (1983), Sidious has become a widely recognized symbol of evil in [[popular culture]], and since the prequel films, also one of sinister deception and the subversion of [[democracy]]. Aside from the films, Sidious appears in various [[Canon (fiction)|canon]] and non-canon [[Star Wars expanded to other media|''Star Wars'' media]], such as [[List of Star Wars books|books]], [[List of Star Wars comic books|comics]], [[List of Star Wars television series|television series]], and [[List of Star Wars video games|video games]].\n\n==Character overview==\n<!-- ATTENTION! PLEASE READ BEFORE EDITING! Please help keep this section brief. Every detail about the plot of Star Wars or Palpatine's life does not need to appear here.-->\nIn the [[fictional universe]] of the ''Star Wars'' franchise, Sidious is a master manipulator and \"phantom menace\".<ref name=\"Databank2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/databank/emperor-palpatine-darth-sidious |title=Emperor Palpatine/Darth Sidious |website=[[Star Wars Databank]] |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Though appearing to be a well-intentioned [[public servant]] and supporter of [[democracy]] before becoming emperor,<ref name=\"Martin M. Winkler 2001. Pp. 287\">{{cite book|first=Martin M.|last=Winkler|title=Classical Myth & Culture in the Cinema|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford, England|date=2001|page=287|isbn=978-0195130041}}</ref> Palpatine is actually '''Darth Sidious''', the dark lord of the [[Sith]]\u2014a cult of practitioners of the [[dark side (Star Wars)|dark side]] of [[the Force]] previously thought to have been extinct for millennia\u2014and master of [[Darth Maul]] and [[Count Dooku]].<ref name=\"Martin M. Winkler 2001. Pp. 287\"/> Sidious masterminds the [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|Clone Wars]], using the conflict as a pretext to grant himself dictatorial [[emergency powers]] and stay in office long after his term expires.<ref name=\"Databank2020\"/>\n\nSidious ultimately reorganizes the [[Galactic Republic|Republic]] into the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]], invokes [[martial law]], and declares himself Emperor. He proceeds to all but exterminate the [[Jedi|Jedi Order]] through [[Order 66 (Star Wars)|Order 66]], and manipulates Jedi Knight [[Anakin Skywalker]] into turning to the dark side and becoming his new apprentice, Darth Vader.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/history-of-palpatine-part-two/ |title=The Emperor Reborn: How the ''Star Wars'' Prequels and the New Disney Canon Reshape Palpatine |publisher=[[/Film]] |date=November 6, 2019|accessdate=January 24, 2020 |first=Adam |last=Frazier}}</ref> Sidious rules [[Star Wars galaxy|the galaxy]] as the Emperor for over two decades before Vader turns on his master and<!--Do NOT use \"seemingly killed\" or related phrases; the source states the Emperor was indeed killed, and this is further confirmed in the 2019 film The Rise of Skywalker--> kills him in order to save his son, [[Luke Skywalker]].<ref name=\"Databank2020\"/>\n\nThirty years later, the Emperor has returned from death.{{efn|name=clone|In ''The Rise of Skywalker'' (2019), Sidious states, \"I have died before\", confirming his death at Vader's hands in ''Return of the Jedi'' (1983).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a30298776/palpatine-return-alive-star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-9-explained/ |title=How the Emperor Returned In ''The Rise of Skywalker'' |location=New York |magazine=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications]] |date=December 21, 2019 |accessdate=December 30, 2019 |first=Matt |last=Miller}}</ref> The Emperor attributes his return to \"abilities some consider to be unnatural\".<ref name=\"Vanity Fair\"/> The novelization of ''The Rise of Skywalker'' expands on the Emperor's return, revealing that he transferred his consciousness into a clone body,<ref>{{cite web |last=Fraser |first=Kevin |title=''Rise of Skywalker'' novel explains how the Emperor survived ''Return of the Jedi'' |url=https://www.joblo.com/movie-news/rise-of-skywalker-novel-explains-how-the-emperor-survived-return-of-the-jedi |website=JoBlo.com |accessdate=March 4, 2020 |date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> similar to the manner of his return in the [[Star Wars expanded to other media|Legends]] comic ''[[Dark Empire]]''&nbsp;(1991).<ref>{{cite web |last=Bacon |first=Thomas |title=''Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker'' Book Confirms Sidious Was A Clone! |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-palpatine-clone-rise-skywalker-confirm-novel/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher= Valnet Inc. |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>}} He is discovered by [[Kylo Ren]], the grandson of Anakin and nephew of Luke. Sidious reveals himself as the puppet master behind the [[First Order (Star Wars)|First Order]] and its former [[Puppet ruler|leader]], [[Supreme Leader Snoke|Snoke]],<ref name=\"Vanity Fair\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-easter-eggs-callbacks-references |title=A Guide to All the Old ''Star Wars'' References in ''The Rise of Skywalker'' |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=December 20, 2019 |accessdate=December 20, 2019 |first1=Joanna |last1=Robinson |first2=Anthony |last2=Breznican |authorlink2=Anthony Breznican}}</ref> and unveils a secret armada of planet-killing [[Star Destroyer]]s to reclaim the galaxy. He orders Kylo to find and kill [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]], the last Jedi, who is revealed to be Sidious' paternal granddaughter.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite web|first=Megan|last=McCluskey|url=https://time.com/5752170/who-are-reys-parents/ |title=Breaking Down That Shocking Rey Reveal in ''Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker'' |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=December 20, 2019 |accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref> Sidious rejuvenates himself using the dark side, but is finally defeated by Rey.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\n==Appearances==\n===Film===\n{{main|Skywalker saga}}\n\n====Original trilogy====\n{{main|Star Wars Trilogy}}\nThe Emperor is briefly mentioned in ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' (1977), the first film in the original trilogy, which was [[Star Wars (film)#Addition of subtitles|later subtitled]] ''Episode IV{{snd}}A New Hope''. [[Grand Moff Tarkin]] ([[Peter Cushing]]) explains to the fellow Imperials that the Emperor has dissolved the Senate,<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars: Episode IV \u2013 A New Hope|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox|location=Los Angeles, California|date=1977|edition=2004}}</ref> but the character does not appear onscreen, leaving [[Darth Vader]] (portrayed by [[David Prowse]], voiced by [[James Earl Jones]]) as the film's main villain.\n\nThe Emperor first appears (in hologram form) in ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'', the 1980 sequel to the original film, to address Vader, informing him that [[Luke Skywalker]] ([[Mark Hamill]]) has become a threat to the Empire. Vader persuades him that the young Jedi would be a great asset if he could be turned to the dark side of the Force.<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\">{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/palpatine/|title=Palpatine|website=Star Wars Databank|accessdate=February 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216025044/http://www.starwars.com:80/databank/character/palpatine |archive-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983's ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'', the Emperor appears in person to oversee the last stages of the [[second Death Star]]'s construction. He assures Vader that they will together turn Luke, Vader's son, to the [[dark side of the Force]]. Unknown to Vader, the Emperor plans to replace his apprentice with Luke, while on the other hand Vader had harboured intentions to overthrow the Emperor and instead rule the galaxy with Luke if he could turn him. When Vader brings Luke before his master, the Emperor tempts Luke to join the dark side by appealing to the young Jedi's fear for his friends, whom he has lured into a trap.<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> This leads to a [[lightsaber]] duel in which Luke defeats and nearly kills Vader. Sidious urges Luke to kill Vader and take his place, but Luke refuses and declares himself a Jedi. Enraged, the Emperor attacks Luke with [[Force lightning]]. Unable to bear the sight of his son in pain, Vader, renouncing the dark side to become Anakin Skywalker again, throws the Emperor into the Death Star\u2019s reactor,<!--Do NOT change to \"seemingly killing\" or related phrases; the source states the Emperor was indeed killed, and this is further confirmed in the 2019 film The Rise of Skywalker--> killing him.<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/>\n\n====Prequel trilogy====\n{{main|Star Wars prequel trilogy}}\n[[File:Palpatine1.jpg|left|thumb|[[Ian McDiarmid]] as Senator Palpatine in ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]'']]\nIn the 1999 prequel ''[[Episode I: The Phantom Menace]]'', set 32 years before ''A New Hope'', Palpatine (named onscreen for the first time) is depicted as a middle-aged Galactic Senator from the planet [[Naboo]].<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> As his [[alter ego]], the Sith Lord Darth Sidious, he advises the corrupt Trade Federation to blockade and invade Naboo.<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> Queen [[Padm\u00e9 Amidala]] of Naboo ([[Natalie Portman]]) flees to the planet [[Coruscant]] to receive counsel from Palpatine, unaware that he actually engineered the invasion. After a plea for help from the Senate results in [[bureaucracy|bureaucratic]] delays, Palpatine persuades Padm\u00e9 to call for a [[motion of no confidence]] against [[Supreme Chancellor]] [[Finis Valorum]] ([[Terence Stamp]]).\n\nWhen Padm\u00e9 attempts to liberate Naboo, Sidious sends his apprentice [[Darth Maul]] (portrayed by [[Ray Park]], voiced by [[Peter Serafinowicz]]) there to capture her. The invasion is eventually thwarted and Maul is defeated in a lightsaber duel with Jedi Padawan [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] ([[Ewan McGregor]]).<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> Palpatine uses the crisis to be elected the new Chancellor of the Republic. He then returns to Naboo, where he befriends the young Anakin Skywalker ([[Jake Lloyd]]), telling the boy, \"We will watch your career with great interest.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox|location=Los Angeles, California|date=1999}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2002 sequel ''[[Episode II: Attack of the Clones]]'', set 10 years later, Palpatine exploits constitutional loopholes to remain in office even after the official expiration of his term. Meanwhile, as Sidious, he continues to manipulate events from behind the scenes by having his new Sith apprentice [[Count Dooku]] ([[Christopher Lee]]) lead a movement of planets in [[Secession|seceding]] to form the [[Confederacy of Independent Systems]].<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> He has the Separatists try to assassinate Padm\u00e9, now a senator, but the attempt on her life fails. He then arranges for Anakin (now played by [[Hayden Christensen]]) to guard Padm\u00e9 on Naboo, which leads to them falling in love and marrying in secret.\n\nWith the Separatists secretly building a [[battle droid]] army, Palpatine uses the situation to have himself granted [[State of emergency|emergency powers]].<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> Palpatine feigns reluctance to accept this authority, promising to return it to the Senate once the crisis has ended. His first act is to allow a clone army's creation to counter the Separatist threat; this results in the first battle of the [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|Clone Wars]]. With the galaxy now at war as Sidious planned, Dooku brings him the secret plans for an [[Death Star|ultimate weapon]].<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode II: Attack of the Clones|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2002}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Darth Sidious.png|thumb|upright|Palpatine as Darth Sidious]]\nIn the 2005 sequel ''[[Episode III: Revenge of the Sith]]'', set three years later, Palpatine is intentionally captured by [[cyborg]] Separatist leader [[General Grievous]] (voiced by [[Matthew Wood (sound editor)|Matthew Wood]]). Palpatine is rescued by Anakin and Obi-Wan, but not before the Jedi confront Dooku again. A duel ensues in which Anakin kills the disarmed and helpless Dooku in cold blood at Palpatine's urging. Palpatine then escapes with his rescuers and returns to Coruscant. By this point, Palpatine has become a virtual dictator, able to take any action in the Senate. He makes Anakin his personal representative on the [[Jedi Council]], whose other members deny Anakin the rank of Jedi Master and order him to spy on the Chancellor. Palpatine tells Anakin the story of [[Darth Plagueis]], a powerful Sith Lord who was able to manipulate life and death but was killed by his own apprentice. Eventually, Palpatine reveals his secret Sith identity to Anakin; he knows that Anakin has been having prophetic visions of Padm\u00e9 dying in childbirth, and offers to teach him Plagueis' secrets to save Padm\u00e9's life.\n\nAnakin informs Jedi Master [[Mace Windu]] ([[Samuel L. Jackson]]) of Palpatine's treachery. With three other Jedi masters at his side, Windu attempts to arrest Sidious, but Sidious produces a lightsaber from his sleeve and quickly dispatches all but Windu. Sidious engages Windu in a duel and fires Force lightning at the Jedi Master, but Windu deflects the lightning back at its source, deforming Sidious' face into the gray, wizened visage first seen in the original trilogy. Just as Windu is about to dispatch Sidious, Anakin appears and intervenes on the Sith lord's behalf, allowing Sidious to kill Windu with another blast of lightning. Anakin then pledges himself to the dark side as Sidious' Sith apprentice, Darth Vader.\n\nSidious issues [[Order 66 (Star Wars)|Order 66]], commanding the clone troopers to turn on their Jedi generals,<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> while dispatching Vader to kill everyone inside the Jedi Temple and then murder the Separatist leaders on the planet [[Mustafar]]. Sidious then reorganizes the Republic into the Galactic Empire, with himself as Emperor.<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> In the Emperor's office, Jedi Master [[Yoda]] (voiced by [[Frank Oz]]) confronts Sidious and engages the Emperor in a lightsaber duel that ends in a stalemate.<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> Sensing that Vader is in danger, Sidious travels to Mustafar and finds his new apprentice near death following a duel with Obi-Wan. After returning to Coruscant, he rebuilds Vader's burned, mutilated body with the black armored suit from the original trilogy. The Emperor then tells Vader that Padm\u00e9 was killed in the heat of Vader's anger, breaking what remains of his apprentice's spirit. The Emperor is last seen watching the original Death Star's construction, with Vader and [[Grand Moff Tarkin|Wilhuff Tarkin]] ([[Wayne Pygram]]) at his side.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2005}}</ref>\n\n====Sequel trilogy====\n{{main|Star Wars sequel trilogy}}\nThe sequel trilogy is set three decades following the events of ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'' (1983). The [[First Order (Star Wars)|First Order]] has risen from the fallen Empire and seeks to destroy the [[New Republic (Star Wars)|New Republic]] and the [[Resistance (Star Wars)|Resistance]]. In the trilogy's first installment, ''[[The Force Awakens]]'' (2015), Darth Sidious' voice can be heard during a vision that the protagonist [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]] ([[Daisy Ridley]]) experiences upon touching Luke Skywalker's lightsaber, which originally belonged to his father, Anakin.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kristen|last=Acuna|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/star-wars-reys-vision-explained-2017-7 | title=A new book reveals details about Rey's vision in 'Star Wars: The Force Awakens' you may have missed before|website=[[Insider Inc.]]|publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]|location=New York City|date=July 26, 2017|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> In ''[[The Last Jedi]]'' (2017), Luke briefly mentions Darth Sidious while explaining the fall of the Jedi Order to Rey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/history-of-palpatine-part-three/ |title=The Emperor Reborn: What Palpatine's Return Means For ''The Rise of Skywalker'' |publisher=[[/Film]] |date=November 7, 2019|accessdate=December 31, 2019 |first=Adam |last=Frazier}}</ref>\n\nDarth Sidious, again played by McDiarmid, appears in the trilogy's final film, ''[[The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (2019). Having returned through \"unnatural\" [[The Force|Force]] abilities,{{efn|name=clone}} the Emperor issues a threat of revenge against the Jedi and the Resistance prior to the film's [[Star Wars opening crawl|opening]]. This prompts First Order leader and fallen Jedi [[Kylo Ren]] ([[Adam Driver]]) to seek him out on the Sith planet [[Exegol]], where a physically impaired Sidious is supported by machinery.<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|first=Christina|last=Schoellkopf|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-12-17/star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-palpatine |title= Emperor Palpatine actor was done with ''Star Wars.'' Then J.J. Abrams called |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=December 17, 2019 |accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Polygon Costume\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/19/21030344/how-is-emperor-palpatine-alive-in-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-snoke-kylo-rey-vader-spoilers |title=Answering the biggest questions about the Emperor's return to ''Star Wars'' |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=December 19, 2019 |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |first=Dave |last=Gonzales}}</ref> Sidious reveals himself as the puppet master behind the First Order and Ren's former master, [[Supreme Leader Snoke|Snoke]] ([[Andy Serkis]]), whom he created to lure Ren to the [[The Force#Depiction|dark side]].<ref name=\"Vanity Fair\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-rise-skywalker-first-order-reveals/ |title=''Star Wars: Rise of Skywalker'' Finally Explains How The First Order Are So Powerful |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet Inc. |date=December 25, 2019 |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |first=Adrienne |last=Tyler}}</ref> He then unveils the Final Order, a massive fleet of superlaser-equipped Star Destroyers. Sidious offers the fleet to Ren on the condition that he find and kill the galaxy's last remaining Jedi, Rey, who is revealed to be the Emperor's granddaughter.<ref name=\"Time\"/> It is subsequently revealed that Sidious had a son,{{efn|name=boba}} who renounced his father; he and his partner took their daughter Rey to the planet [[Jakku]], assuming lives as \"nobodies\" to keep her safe. Sidious eventually found Rey's parents and had them killed, but never found Rey.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\nNear the end of the film, Rey arrives on Exegol to confront Sidious, who presides over the [[Sith#Sith Eternal|Sith Eternal]], cultists dedicated to the rebirth of the Sith.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2019/12/21/star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-exegol-sith-planet-wayfinder-explained |title=''Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker's'' Hidden Planet Explained |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=December 21, 2019 |accessdate=December 25, 2019 |first=Jesse |last=Schedeen}}</ref> Sidious orders Rey to kill him as a sacrifice to transfer his spirit into her, making her \"Empress Palpatine\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-rise-skywalker-palpatine-plan-sith-ritual/ |title=''Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker'' - Sidious' Plan & Sith Ritual Explained |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet Inc. |date=December 26, 2019 |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |first=Craig |last=Elvy}}</ref> Rey refuses; she and Ren, who has since renounced the dark side and reclaimed his identity of Ben Solo, confront him together. Sensing their power as a [[Dyad (sociology)|dyad]] in the Force, the Emperor absorbs their life energy to restore his full power. He casts Ben down a ravine and attacks the Resistance fleet with Force lightning. Rey uses the power of the past Jedi to regain her strength and face the Emperor once more; he attacks her with his lightning, but Rey deflects it using the [[Skywalker family|Skywalker]] lightsabers, finally killing him.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\n===Television===\n====''The Clone Wars''====\nIn the 2008 animated film ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' and the [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|subsequent animated series]] (set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''), Sidious continues to serve as Supreme Chancellor Palpatine while he orchestrates the Clone Wars behind the scenes. Sidious was voiced by [[Ian Abercrombie]] (from 2008 to his death in 2012), and by [[Tim Curry]] (from 2012 to 2014).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/01/arts/television/ian-abercrombie-elaines-boss-on-seinfeld-dies-at-77.html |title=Ian Abercrombie, Who Played the Boss on ''Seinfeld'', Dies at 77 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 1, 2012 |accessdate=January 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/tim-curry-star-wars_b_2776241 |title=\nExclusive: Tim Curry Joins ''Star Wars'' |newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=February 28, 2013 |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |first=Bryan |last=Young}}</ref> In the film, Sidious engineers a Separatist plot where Count Dooku (voiced by [[Corey Burton]]) turns [[Jabba the Hutt]] against the Republic by kidnapping his son Rotta and framing the Jedi for it. Meanwhile, Palpatine suggests that the Republic ally itself with the Hutts. Although Anakin Skywalker and his Padawan [[Ahsoka Tano]] (voiced by [[Ashley Eckstein]]) foil the plot, the outcome suits Palpatine's ends: Jabba places Hutt [[hyperspace (science fiction)|hyperspace]] routes at the Republic's disposal.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]|date=2008}}</ref>\n\nIn season two of the TV series, Sidious hires bounty hunter [[Cad Bane]] (voiced by [[Corey Burton]]) to infiltrate the Jedi Temple and steal a [[holocron]]. He then takes a valuable Kyber memory crystal that contains the names of thousands of Force-sensitive younglings \u2013 the future of the Jedi Order \u2013 from around the galaxy. The final stage of the plot: to bring four Force-sensitive children to Sidious' secret facility on Mustafar. Anakin and Ahsoka again foil the plot, but Bane escapes and all evidence of Sidious' involvement is lost.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]] Season 2: Rise of the Bounty Hunters|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Warner Bros. Television]]|date=2009}}</ref> In season three, Sidious senses Dooku's minion [[Asajj Ventress]] (voiced by [[Nika Futterman]]) becoming powerful in the dark side and orders Dooku to eliminate her; he suspects that Dooku is planning to have Ventress assassinate him. Ventress survives and her revenge against Dooku sets off a chain of events including the return of Sidious' former apprentice and Dooku's predecessor, Darth Maul.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]] Season 3: Secrets Revealed|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Warner Bros. Television]]|date=2010}}</ref>\n\nIn season five, Sidious personally travels to the planet [[Mandalore]] to confront Maul, who has become the leader of Death Watch. Sidious kills [[Savage Opress]] (voiced by [[Clancy Brown]]) before torturing Maul with the intent to make use of his former apprentice. In season six, Sidious goes to lengths to conceal his plan's full nature from the Jedi by silencing Clone Trooper Fives from learning of Order 66, and having Dooku wipe out anything tied to the former Jedi Master's [[Sifo-Dyas|connection]] to the conspiracy.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]] Season 5|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Warner Bros. Television]]|date=2012\u201313}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]] Season 6: The Lost Missions|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Lucasfilm]] Ltd.|date=2014}}</ref>\n\n====''Rebels''====\nIn ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]'', set between ''Revenge of the Sith'' and ''A New Hope'', Darth Sidious is portrayed as the Emperor of the Galactic Empire. He briefly appears off-screen at the end of season two's premiere \"[[List of Star Wars Rebels episodes#Season 2 (2015-16)|The Siege of Lothal]]\" (originally voiced by [[Sam Witwer]] and later [[Ian McDiarmid]] from 2019). Darth Vader informs the Emperor that the [[Rebel Alliance]] cell on [[List of Star Wars planets and moons|Lothal]] has been broken. Vader also tells him that Ahsoka Tano is alive and is now helping the Rebels. The Emperor sees this as an opportunity to seek out other remaining Jedi. The Emperor then orders Vader to dispatch an Inquisitor to hunt down Ahsoka.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Star Wars Rebels]] [[List of Star Wars Rebels episodes#Season 2 (2015\u201316)|Season 2]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney]]|date=2015}}</ref>\n\nSidious returns physically in season four (voiced again by McDiarmid). In the episodes \"Wolves and a Door\" and \"A World Between Worlds\", he appears as a hologram overseeing the excavation of the Lothal [[Jedi Temple]], which contains a portal to a separate dimension of the Force outside of space and time, which the Emperor considers a 'conduit between the living and the dead' that could give him unrivaled power of the Force itself if he can access it. Shortly after protagonist [[Ezra Bridger]] (voiced by [[Taylor Gray]]) reaches through time and space to rescue Ahsoka from Vader, the Emperor sets up a portal that shows [[Kanan Jarrus]]' (voiced by [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]) final moments. While Ezra wants to reach through the portal and rescue Kanan, Ahsoka convinces him not to. The Emperor then reveals himself through the portal and shoots Ezra with Force lightning. However, Ahsoka and Ezra manage to evade him and go their separate ways, thus denying Sidious full power.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=[[Star Wars Rebels]] [[List of Star Wars Rebels episodes#Season 4 (2017\u201318)|Season 4]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney]]|date=2017}}</ref>\n\nSidious later returns in the [[series finale]] \"Family Reunion - and Farewell\". In the episode, Ezra, having surrendered himself to [[Grand Admiral Thrawn]] (voiced by [[Lars Mikkelsen]]) to protect Lothal, is taken by him to a room containing a reconstructed section of the ruined Jedi Temple and a hologram of Sidious as he appears in the prequel films. The Emperor, having acknowledged the threat Ezra poses to the Empire, presents himself as a kindly figure and shows Ezra a vision of his dead parents through a doorway, promising that the youth will be with them if he enters it. Ezra is initially mesmerized by the Emperor's promise and goes to enter the door, but finally resists and destroys the reconstructed Jedi Temple and the illusion. The Emperor's hologram emerges from the rubble, flickering to show his true self, and commands his Royal Guards to kill Ezra, though Ezra manages to defeat them and escape. According to series creator [[Dave Filoni]], the events of ''[[Rogue One]]'' and ''A New Hope'' happen shortly after this episode, thus refocusing the Emperor's attention from Ezra and Lothal's liberation to the Rebel Alliance and Luke Skywalker.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Hanh|last=Nguyen|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/03/star-wars-rebels-finale-sabine-ezra-dave-filoni-1201936350/|title='Star Wars Rebels' Finale: That Surprise Ending Cameo, Ezra's Big Face-Off, and Possibilities for the Future|website=[[IndieWire]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=March 6, 2018|access-date=June 23, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Books and comics===\nThe first appearance of Sidious in ''Star Wars'' literature was in the prologue of [[Alan Dean Foster]]'s ghostwritten novelization of the script of ''A New Hope'', published as ''[[Star Wars: From the Adventures of Luke Skywalker]]'' (1976).<ref name=\"Lucas1\">{{cite book|first1=George|last1=Lucas|authorlink1=George Lucas|first2=Alan Dean|last2=Foster|authorlink2=Alan Dean Foster|title=Star Wars: From the Adventures of Luke Skywalker|medium=paperback|publisher=[[Del Ray Books]]|location=New York City|date=1976|page=1|isbn=978-0-345-26079-6}}</ref>{{sfn|Kaminski|2008|p=172}} His background as a senator of the Republic was also further explored in [[James Kahn]]'s [[Return of the Jedi (novel)|novelization of ''Return of the Jedi'']].<ref name=kahn/>\nSidious appears in [[Rae Carson]]'s [[The Rise of Skywalker#Tie-in literature and merchandise|novelization of ''The Rise of Skywalker'']], which expands upon the film's story. In the book, Sidious is revealed to have discovered his former master Darth Plagueis's \"secret to immortality\", using this knowledge to survive after his death in ''Return of the Jedi''.<ref name=\"ROS Novel\">{{cite book|first=Rae|last=Carson|title=Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker Expanded Edition |publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|date=2020|isbn=978-0593128404}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2020/03/04/star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-emperor-palpatine-return-darth-plagueis/ |title=''Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker'' Novelization Details How the Emperor Survived the Death Star II, Thanks to Plagueis |website=Comicbook.com |date=March 4, 2020 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |first=Patrick |last=Cavanaugh}}</ref>{{efn|name=clone}} The character also appears in the final chapter of the comic book ''Star Wars: The Rise of Kylo Ren'' (2020), which illustrates Sidious' manipulation of the young Ben Solo into becoming Kylo Ren.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2020/03/11/star-wars-rise-kylo-ren-4-ben-solo-palpatine-influence-snoke-connections/ |title=''Star Wars'' Reveals How Sidious Turned Ben Solo into Kylo Ren |website=Comicbook.com |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |first=Kofi |last=Outlaw}}</ref>\n\n''[[Star Wars: Lords of the Sith]]'' (2015) was one of the first canon spin-off novels to be released in the [[Disney]] canon begun in 2014.<ref name=\"SW Adult\"/> In it, Vader and Sidious find themselves hunted by revolutionaries on the [[Twi'lek]] home planet [[Ryloth]].<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite web |first=Sean |last=Keane |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/pageviews/review-star-wars-lords-sith-blog-entry-1.2201665 |title=REVIEW: ''Star Wars: Lords of the Sith'' throws Darth Vader and the Emperor onto the battlefield |newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=New York City|date=April 28, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Goldman |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/09/star-wars-lords-of-the-sith-review |title=''Star Wars: Lords of the Sith'' Review |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[j2 Global]]|location=New York City|date=May 9, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> In ''[[Star Wars: Thrawn|Thrawn]]'', the [[Thrawn|titular character]] warns Sidious of \"threats lurking in the Unknown Regions.\" [[Chuck Wendig]]'s ''[[Star Wars: Aftermath|Aftermath]]'' book trilogy reveals that, prior to his death, Sidious enacted a plan for the remnants of the Empire to retreat to the Unknown Regions, where they formed into the [[First Order]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ratcliffe |first=Amy |title=The Possibilities of the Unknown Regions in STAR WARS |url=https://nerdist.com/article/star-wars-unknown-regions/ |website=Nerdist |accessdate=April 26, 2019 |date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> The dark side was thought to be concentrated in this region, where one Sith cultist believed that Sidious would be found alive.<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen M. |last=Colbert |title=Star Wars 9 Theory: Snoke Was Actually Darth Sidious All Along |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-9-snoke-palpatine-true-identity/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet, Inc.|location=Montreal, Ontario, Canada|accessdate=April 26, 2019 |date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDarth Sidious also appears frequently in the comic book series ''[[Darth Vader: Dark Lord of the Sith]]'' (2017\u20132018), written by Kieron Gillen and Charles Soule. It is suggested at the end of the series that Sidious manipulated the Force to impregnate Vader's mother [[Shmi Skywalker]], making him in essence Vader's father\u2014although this is left somewhat ambiguous.<ref name=slash>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/darth-vaders-father-revealed/|title=Darth Vader's Father Revealed in Star Wars Comic?|last=Young|first=Bryan|date=December 28, 2018|website=[[/Film]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> This builds on the plot point of Anakin's [[Miraculous births|virgin birth]] introduced in ''The Phantom Menace'', and the claim that a Sith lord \"could use the Force to influence the [[midi-chlorians]] to create life,\" as Sidious tells Anakin in ''Revenge of the Sith''.{{efn|In the rough draft of the latter film, Sidious explicitly tells Anakin that he \"used the power of the Force to will the midichlorians to start the [[cell division]]s\" that conceived him.<ref name=slash/>}} This would seem to have incestuous implications for Rey and Ben Solo at the end of ''The Rise of Skywalker'',<ref>{{cite web |last=Gramuglia |first=Anthony |title=Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker Might Have More Accidental Incest |url=https://www.cbr.com/star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-accidental-incest/ |website=[[Comic Book Resources|CBR]] |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |date=December 25, 2019}}</ref> but Soule says that \"The Dark Side is not a reliable narrator,\" and a [[Lucasfilm]] Story Group member who collaborated on the comic confirms that a direct connection between the Emperor and Vader was not their intent.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lovett |first=Jamie |title=Star Wars Story Group Member Debunks Palpatine and Anakin Theory |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/12/24/star-wars-darth-vader-emperor-palpatine-father-darth-plagueis/ |website=Comicbook.com |accessdate=December 25, 2019 |date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n''[[Star Wars Battlefront II (2017 video game)|Star Wars Battlefront II]]'' adds a canonical tale spanning the destruction of the second [[Death Star]] through the events of ''[[The Force Awakens]]''. The story takes an Imperial perspective, following an elite squadron known as Inferno Squad, led by protagonist [[Iden Versio]], as they help to execute ''Operation: Cinder'' following the Emperor\u2019s death. ''Operation: Cinder'' was carried out by the Galactic Empire as a means of devastating several Imperial planets a few weeks after the Battle of Endor. The operation was part of the \"Contingency\", a plan devised by the Emperor to ensure that the Empire and its enemies would not outlive him should he perish. The plan was put into action following the Emperor's death during the [[Battle of Endor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-palpatine-plan-after-death/ |title=''Star Wars'': Sidious\u2019 Plan For After His Death Revealed |website=[[Screen Rant]] |publisher=Valnet Inc. |date=June 23, 2019 |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |first=Thomas |last=Bacon}}</ref>\n\nSidious' threat of revenge referenced in the [[Star Wars opening crawl|opening crawl]] of ''The Rise of Skywalker'' was included in the finale of the ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale|Fortnite: Battle Royale]] X Star Wars'' event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-rise-skywalker-emperor-palpatine-message-fortnite/ |title=''Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker'' Explains Missing Plot Point... In ''Fortnite'' |website=[[Screenrant]] |publisher=Valnet Inc. |date=December 24, 2019 |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |first=Thomas |last=Bacon}}</ref>\n\n===''Legends''===\nIn April 2014, Lucasfilm rebranded most of the licensed ''Star Wars'' novels and comics produced since the originating 1977 film ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' as ''[[Star Wars expanded universe|Star Wars Legends]]'' and declared them non-canon to the franchise.<ref name=\"THR Legends\">{{cite magazine |first=Graeme|last=McMilian |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lucasfilm-unveils-new-plans-star-698973 |title=Lucasfilm Unveils New Plans for ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SW Legends\">{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/the-legendary-star-wars-expanded-universe-turns-a-new-page |title=The Legendary ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe Turns a New Page |publisher=[[StarWars.com]] |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SW Adult\">{{cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/disney-publishing-worldwide-and-random-house-announce-relaunch-of-star-wars-adult-fiction-line |title=Disney and Random House announce relaunch of ''Star Wars'' Adult Fiction line |publisher=StarWars.com |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> ''Star Wars Legends'' literature elaborates on Sidious' role in ''Star Wars'' fiction outside of the films.\n\n====Television====\n<!-- ATTENTION! PLEASE READ BEFORE EDITING! Please help keep this section brief. Every detail about the plot of Star Wars or Sidious' life does not need to appear here. -->\n[[File:PalpatineCloneWar.JPG|thumb|Chancellor Palpatine in ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'']]\nPalpatine/Darth Sidious is a central character in [[Genndy Tartakovsky]]'s ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'' micro-series, which is set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''. The character's likeness in the series is voiced by [[Nick Jameson]]. In the first chapter, Palpatine is informed by Obi-Wan Kenobi (voiced by [[James Arnold Taylor]]) that the Jedi have discovered that the InterGalactic Banking Clan has established battle droid factories on the planet [[Muunilinst]]. Palpatine agrees to send a strike force that includes Anakin Skywalker (voiced by [[Matt Lanter]]), and suggests that Anakin be given \"special command\" of Obi-Wan's fighters. Yoda and Obi-Wan initially speak against the idea, but reluctantly concede.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Chapter 1|series=Star Wars: Clone Wars|serieslink=Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|network=Cartoon Network|airdate= November 7, 2003|season=1|number=1}}</ref> In the seventh chapter, a holographic image of Sidious appears shortly after Dooku trains [[Dark Jedi]] [[Asajj Ventress]] (voiced by [[Grey DeLisle]]). Sidious orders Ventress to track down and kill Anakin. He remarks to Dooku that Ventress is certain to be defeated, but that the point of her mission is to test Anakin.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Chapter 7|series=Star Wars: Clone Wars|serieslink=Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|network=Cartoon Network|airdate= November 17, 2003|season=1|number=7}}</ref> In the final chapters, a hologram of Sidious again appears and orders General Grievous to begin an assault on the galactic capital.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Chapter 22|series=Star Wars: Clone Wars|serieslink=Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|network=[[Cartoon Network]]|airdate=March 22, 2003|season=3|number=2}}</ref> Later, the Separatist invasion of Coruscant begins and Palpatine watches from his apartment in the 500 Republica. Grievous breaks through the Chancellor's window and attempts to kidnap him,<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Chapter 23|series=Star Wars: Clone Wars|serieslink=Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|network=[[Cartoon Network]]|airdate= March 23, 2005|season=3|number=3}}</ref> leading to a long chase while Palpatine is protected by Jedi [[Shaak Ti]] (voiced by [[Tasia Valenza]]), Roron Corobb and Foul Moudama. After Grievous apprehends the Jedi, Palpatine is taken on board the ''Invisible Hand'', setting the stage for ''Revenge of the Sith''.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Chapter 25|series=Star Wars: Clone Wars|serieslink=Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|network=[[Cartoon Network]]|airdate= March 25, 2005|season=3|number=5}}</ref>\n\n====Books and comics====\n<!-- ATTENTION! PLEASE READ BEFORE EDITING! Please help keep this section brief. Every detail about the plot of Star Wars or Palpatine's life does not need to appear here. -->\nDarth Sidious made his first major appearance in ''Star Wars''-related comic books in 1991 and 1992, with the ''[[Dark Empire]]'' series written by [[Tom Veitch]] and illustrated by [[Cam Kennedy]]. In the series (set six years after ''Return of the Jedi''), Sidious is resurrected as the Emperor Reborn or \"Palpatine the Undying\". His spirit returns from the netherworld of the Force with the aid of Sith ghosts on [[Korriban]], and [[spiritual possession|possesses]] the body of [[Jeng Droga]], one of Sidious' elite spies and assassins known as the Emperor's Hands. Droga flees to a secret Imperial base on the planet [[Byss]], where the Emperor's advisor Sate Pestage [[exorcism|exorcises]] Sidious' spirit and channels it into one of many [[cloning|clones]] created by the Emperor before his death. Sidious attempts to resume control of the galaxy, but Luke Skywalker, now a senior Jedi Knight, sabotages his plans. Luke destroys most of Sidious' cloning tanks, but is only able to defeat the Emperor with help from [[Princess Leia|Leia Organa Solo]], who has received rudimentary Jedi training from Luke. The two repel a Force storm Sidious had created and turn it back onto him, once again destroying his physical form.<ref>{{cite comic|writer=[[Tom Veitch]]|title=Dark Empire|publisher=[[Dark Horse Comics]]|location=Milwaukie, Oregon|date=1993}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Swhde16 bg.JPG|thumb|upright|left|Sidious' clone in the ''[[Dark Empire]]'' series by [[Tom Veitch]] and [[Cam Kennedy]]]]\nSidious' ultimate fate is further chronicled in the ''[[Dark Empire II]]'' and ''[[Empire's End]]'' series of comics. The ''Dark Empire II'' series, published from 1994 to 1995, details how the Emperor is once again reborn on Byss into a clone body. Sidious tries to rebuild the Empire as the Rebel Alliance grows weak.<ref>{{cite comic|writer=Tom Veitch|title=[[Dark Empire II]]|publisher=[[Dark Horse Comics]]|location=Milwaukie, Oregon|date=1995}}</ref> In ''Empire's End'' (1995), a traitorous Imperial guard bribes Sidious' cloning supervisor to tamper with the Emperor's stored [[DNA]] samples. This causes the clones to deteriorate at a rapid rate. Sidious tries to possess the body of [[Anakin Solo]], the infant son of Leia Organa and [[Han Solo]], before the clone body dies, but is thwarted once again by Luke Skywalker. Sidious is killed by a blaster shot fired by Han, but his spirit is captured by the mortally wounded Jedi [[Empatojayos Brand]]. When Brand dies, he takes Sidious' spirit with him into the netherworld of the Force, destroying the Sith Lord once and for all.<ref>{{cite comic|writer=Tom Veitch|title=[[Empire's End]]|publisher=[[Dark Horse Comics]]|location=Milwaukie, Oregon|date=1997}}</ref>\n\nNovels and comics published before 1999 focus on Darth Sidious' role as Galactic Emperor. ''[[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire (novel)|Shadows of the Empire]]'' (1996) by [[Steve Perry (author)|Steve Perry]] and ''[[The Mandalorian Armor]]'' (1998) by [[K. W. Jeter]]\u2014all set between ''The Empire Strikes Back'' and ''Return of the Jedi''\u2014show how Sidious uses crime lords such as [[Prince Xizor]] and [[bounty hunter]]s like [[Boba Fett]] to fight his enemies.<ref>{{cite book|first=Steve|last=Perry|title=Shadows of the Empire|publisher=Bantam Spectra|location=New York City|date=1996|isbn=978-0-553-57413-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=K. W.|last=Jeter|title=The Mandalorian Armor|publisher=Bantam Spectra|location=New York City|date=1998|page=144|isbn=978-0-553-57885-0}}</ref> [[Barbara Hambly]]'s novel ''[[Children of the Jedi]]'' (1995), set eight years after ''Return of the Jedi'', features a woman named [[Roganda Ismaren]] who claims that Sidious fathered her son [[Irek Ismaren|Irek]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Barbara|last=Hambly|title=Children of the Jedi|publisher=[[Bantam Spectra]]|location=New York City|date=1996|isbn=978-0-553-57293-3|title-link=Children of the Jedi}}</ref> The ''[[Jedi Prince]]'' series of novels introduces an insane, three-eyed [[mutant]] named [[List of Star Wars characters#T|Triclops]] who is revealed to be Sidious' illegitimate son.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Paul|last1=Davids|first2=Hollace|last2=Davids|title=Mission from Mount Yoda|publisher=[[Scholastic Books]]|location=New York City|date=1993|isbn=978-0-553-15890-8|title-link=Mission from Mount Yoda}}</ref> Created from [[DNA]] extracted from Sidious and placed into a woman, he was born mutated, cast away and forgotten. Triclops had a son named [[Exar Kun|Ken]] who became known as the \"Jedi Prince\".\n\nAfter the release of ''The Phantom Menace'', writers were allowed to begin exploring Sidious' backstory as a politician and Sith lord. The comic \"Marked\" by [[Rob Williams (comics)|Rob Williams]], printed in ''[[Star Wars Tales 24]]'' (2005), and [[Michael Reaves]]' novel ''[[Darth Maul: Shadow Hunter]]'' (2001) explain Darth Sidious' relationship with his apprentice Darth Maul.<ref>{{cite comic|writer=Rob Williams|story=Marked|title=[[Star Wars Tales]]|volume=24|publisher=[[Dark Horse Comics]]|location=Milwaukie, Oregon|date=July 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Michael|last=Reaves|authorlink=Michael Reaves|title=Darth Maul: Shadow Hunter|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=New York City|year=2001|isbn=978-0-345-43541-5|title-link=Darth Maul: Shadow Hunter}}</ref> ''[[Cloak of Deception]]'' (2001) by [[James Luceno]] follows Reaves' novel and details how Darth Sidious encourages the Trade Federation to build an army of battle droids in preparation for the invasion of Naboo. ''Cloak of Deception'' also focuses on Sidious' early political career as Palpatine, revealing how he becomes a confidante of Chancellor Finis Valorum and acquainted with Padm\u00e9 Amidala, newly elected queen of Naboo.<ref>{{cite book|first=James|last=Luceno|authorlink=James Luceno|title=Cloak of Deception|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=New York City|date=2001|isbn=978-0-345-44297-0}}</ref> Palpatine's role during the Clone Wars as Chancellor of the Republic and Darth Sidious is portrayed in novels such as [[Matthew Stover]]'s ''[[Shatterpoint]]'' (2003), [[Steven Barnes]]' ''[[The Cestus Deception]]'' (2004), [[Sean Stewart]]'s ''[[Yoda: Dark Rendezvous]]'' (2004), and Luceno's ''[[Labyrinth of Evil]]'' (2005) and ''[[Darth Plagueis]]'' (2012).\n\nFollowing the theatrical release of ''Revenge of the Sith'', ''Star Wars'' literature focused on Sidious' role after the creation of the Empire. [[John Ostrander]]'s comic ''Star Wars Republic 78: Loyalties'' (2005) chronicles how, shortly after seizing power, the Emperor sends Darth Vader to assassinate Sagoro Autem, an Imperial captain who plans to defect from the Empire.<ref>{{cite comic|writer=[[John Ostrander]]|story=Loyalties|title=[[Star Wars: Republic]]|issue=78|publisher=[[Dark Horse Comics]]|location=Milwaukie, Oregon|date=October 2005}}</ref> In Luceno's novel ''[[Dark Lord: The Rise of Darth Vader]]'' (2005) (set shortly after ''Revenge of the Sith''), the Emperor sends Darth Vader to the planet Murkhana to discover why clone troopers there refused to carry out [[Great Jedi Purge|Order 66]] against their Jedi generals. Sidious hopes these early missions will teach Vader what it means to be a Sith and crush any remnants of Anakin Skywalker.<ref>{{cite book|first=James|last=Luceno|authorlink=James Luceno|title=Dark Lord: The Rise of Darth Vader|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=New York City|date=2005|isbn=978-0-345-47733-0|title-link=Dark Lord: The Rise of Darth Vader}}</ref>\n\n==Characterization==\n[[File:EmperorCliveESB1980.jpg|thumb|280px|The Emperor in the original 1980 version of ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'' portrayed by [[Marjorie Eaton]]<ref name=\"Hidalgo twitter\"/> and voiced by [[Clive Revill]]. To make his face appear more frightening, elements of chimpanzee face were incorporated.]]\n\n<!-- ATTENTION! Please keep this section brief! Every detail about Star Wars or Sidious' life does not need to appear here. -->\nIn ''Star Wars'' fiction, Sidious is a cunning politician, a ruthless emperor, and an evil Sith Lord. The [[Star Wars Databank|''Star Wars'' Databank]] describes him as \"the supreme ruler of the most powerful tyrannical regime the galaxy had ever witnessed\"<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> and [[Stephen J. Sansweet]]'s ''[[Star Wars Encyclopedia]]'' calls him \"evil incarnate\".<ref name=\"Sansweet224\">{{cite encyclopedia |editor-first=Stephen J. |editor-last=Sansweet |editor-link=Stephen J. Sansweet |encyclopedia=[[Star Wars Encyclopedia]] |title=Emperor Palpatine |date=1998 |publisher=[[Del Ray Books]] |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-345-40227-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/starwarsencyclop00sans/page/224 224] |url=https://archive.org/details/starwarsencyclop00sans/page/224 }}</ref>\n\nAs a senator, Palpatine is \"unassuming, yet ambitious\".<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> In ''Cloak of Deception'', James Luceno writes that Sidious carefully guards his privacy and \"others found his reclusiveness intriguing, as if he led a secret life\".<ref name=\"Luceno124\">{{cite book|first=James|last=Luceno|authorlink=James Luceno|title=Cloak of Deception|publisher=[[Del Ray Books]]|location=New York City|date=2002|isbn=978-0345442970|page=124|title-link=Cloak of Deception}}</ref> Despite this, he has many allies in the government. Luceno writes, \"What Sidious lacked in charisma, he made up for in candor, and it was that directness that had led to his widespread appeal in the senate. ... For in his heart he judged the universe on his own terms, with a clear sense of right and wrong.\"<ref name=\"Luceno124\"/> In [[Terry Brooks]]' [[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace (novel)|novelization of ''The Phantom Menace'']], Sidious claims to embrace democratic principles. He tells Queen Amidala, \"I promise, Your Majesty, if I am elected [chancellor of the Republic], I will restore democracy to the Republic. I will put an end to the corruption that has plagued the Senate.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=Terry|last=Brooks|authorlink=Terry Brooks|title=Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=New York City|pages=[https://archive.org/details/phantommenace00broo_0/page/238 238\u2013239]|date=1999|isbn=978-0-345-43411-1|title-link=Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace (novel)}}</ref> A ''Visual Dictionary'' states that he is a self-proclaimed savior.<ref name=visual>{{cite encyclopedia|first=James|last=Luceno|author-link=James Luceno|title=The Visual Dictionary of Star Wars, Episode III Revenge of the Sith |publisher=Dorling Kindersley Publishing, Inc. |location=London, England|date=2005|isbn=978-0-7566-1128-6|page=100}}</ref>\n\nAs Emperor, however, Sidious abandons any semblance of democracy, as noted in ''A New Hope'', when he abolishes the Imperial Senate. Sansweet states, \"His Empire ... is based on tyranny.\"<ref name=\"Sansweet224\"/>\n\n''Revenge of the Sith'' implies that Sidious was the apprentice of Darth Plagueis, while later Expanded Universe materials say explicitly that he was.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/darthsidious/index.html|title=Darth Sidious|website=Star Wars Databank|accessdate=August 17, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205030541/http://starwars.com/databank/character/darthsidious |archive-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Sidious is characterized as \"the most powerful practitioner of the Sith ways in modern times.\"<ref name=\"SidiousEU\">{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/palpatine/?id=eu|title=Darth Sidious, Expanded Universe|website=Star Wars Databank|accessdate=August 17, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061201010639/http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/palpatine/?id=eu |archive-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Darth Sidious is so powerful that he is able to mask his true identity from the Jedi for decades. In the novel ''[[Shatterpoint]]'', Mace Windu remarks to Yoda, \"A shame [Sidious] can't touch the Force. He might have been a fine Jedi.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=Matthew|last=Stover|authorlink=Matthew Stover|title=Shatterpoint|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=New York City|date=2003|page=[https://archive.org/details/shatterpointstar00matt/page/10 10]|isbn=978-0-345-45574-1|title-link=Shatterpoint}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Star Wars'' Databank explains that the Force \"granted him inhuman dexterity and speed, agility enough to quickly kill three Jedi Masters\" (as depicted in ''Revenge of the Sith'').<ref name=\"PalpatineDatabank\"/> Stover describes the duel between Yoda and Sidious in his [[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith (novel)|novelization of ''Revenge of the Sith'']] thus: \"From the shadow of a black wing, a small weapon&nbsp;... slid into a withered hand and spat a flame-colored blade ... When those blades met, it was more than Yoda against Sidious, more the millennia of Sith against the legions of Jedi; this was the expression of the fundamental conflict of the universe itself. Light against dark. Winner take all.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=Matthew|last=Stover|authorlink=Matthew Stover|title=Revenge of the Sith|publisher=[[Del Ray Books]]|location=New York City|isbn=978-0345428844|date=2005|page=[https://archive.org/details/revengeofsith00stov/page/424 424]|title-link=Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith (novel)}}</ref> During the duel, Yoda realizes that Sidious is a superior warrior, and represents a small but powerful Sith Order that had changed and evolved over the years, while the Jedi had not: \"He had lost before he started. He had lost before he was born.\"<ref>Stover, page 426</ref>\n\nAccording to the Databank and ''New Essential Guide to Characters'', Sidious possesses great patience and his maneuverings are as a dejarik grandmaster moves pieces on a board.<ref name=negc>{{cite encyclopedia|first1=Daniel|last1=Wallace|first2=Michael|last2=Sutfin|title=The New Essential Guide to Characters|entry=the Emperor|publisher=[[Del Ray Books]]|location=New York City|date=2002|isbn=978-0-345-44900-9}}</ref> He is depicted as a diabolical [[genius]].<ref name=rulebook>{{cite book|first1=Bill|last1=Slavicsek|first2=Andy|last2=Collins|first3=J.D.|last3=Wiker|first4=Steven J.|last4=Sansweet|title=Revised Core Rulebook (Star Wars Roleplaying Game)|publisher=[[Wizards of the Coast]]|location=Renton, Washington|date=2002|isbn=978-0-7869-2876-7}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sideshowtoy.com/behindtheshow/?page_id=1389 Movie, Television and Proprietary Collectible Figures - Sideshow Collectibles, Inc. - Toy, WETA, Lord of the Rings, James Bond, Muppets, Military, Universal Monsters<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122132846/http://www.sideshowtoy.com/behindtheshow/?page_id=1389 |date=2008-01-22 }}</ref>\n\nDarth Sidious was not given a first name in any [[Star Wars canon|canonical]] or \"''Star Wars'' Legends\" sources until 2014, when the character's first name\u2014Sheev\u2014was revealed in the novel ''[[Star Wars: Tarkin|Tarkin]]'', written by [[James Luceno]].<ref name=\"Tarkin book\">{{cite book|first=James|last=Luceno|author-link=James Luceno|title=Tarkin|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=New York City|date=2014|isbn=9780345511522|page=93}}</ref> The Lucasfilm Story Group approached [[Del Rey Books]] and asked if they wanted to use the name, which was created by [[George Lucas]], in the ''Tarkin'' novel, to which Del Rey agreed.<ref name=\"NYCC A New Dawn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OiG16jfqxPQ|title=NYCC 2014 Star Wars Books Panel|work=The Star Wars Underworld (YouTube page)|date=October 11, 2014|accessdate=October 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Creation===\nLucas' conceptualization of Sidious and the role the character plays in ''Star Wars'' changed over time. From ''Return of the Jedi'' onwards, Sidious became the ultimate personification of evil in ''Star Wars'', replacing Darth Vader as the central villain.\n\nWhen the original ''Star Wars'' trilogy was filmed, the Emperor was unnamed and his throne-world unidentified. The name would not be used in film until the prequel trilogy, and the first mention of the name Sidious came from the prologue of Alan Dean Foster's 1976 novelization of ''A New Hope'', which detailed the Emperor's rise to power. Foster writes,\n\n{{quote|Aided and abetted by restless, power-hungry individuals within the government, and the massive organs of commerce, the ambitious Senator Palpatine caused himself to be elected President of the Republic. He promised to reunite the disaffected among the people and to restore the remembered glory of the Republic. Once secure in office he declared himself Emperor, shutting himself away from the populace. Soon he was controlled by the very assistants and boot-lickers he had appointed to high office, and the cries of the people for justice did not reach his ears.<ref name=\"Lucas1\"/>}}\n\nIt is unclear whether Lucas intended Sidious to be the reigning Emperor or just the first of a succession of emperors. In ''The Secret History of Star Wars'', Michael Kaminski states that Lucas' initial notes discuss a line of corrupt emperors, not just one. If Sidious was the first, Kaminski infers, he would therefore not be the current emperor.{{sfn|Kaminski|2008|pp=170\u2013172}} However, by the time of ''Return of the Jedi'' and its novelization, Sidious was made the name of the current emperor.<ref name=kahn>{{cite book |last=Kahn |first=James |title=Star Wars: Episode VI \u2013 Return of the Jedi |date=1983 |publisher=Del Rey Books |location=New York |isbn=0-345-30767-4 |p=69}}</ref>\n\nDuring story conferences for ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'', Lucas and [[Leigh Brackett]] decided that \"the Emperor and the Force had to be the two main concerns in [the film]; the Emperor had barely been dealt with in the first movie, and the intention in the sequel was to deal with him on a more concrete level.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=Star Wars: The Annotated Screenplays|publisher=[[Ballantine Books]]|location=New York City|isbn=978-0345409812|page=173|year=1997}}</ref> Lucas ultimately decided instead to focus on the Emperor in ''Return of the Jedi''.\n\n[[File:Richard M. Nixon, ca. 1935 - 1982 - NARA - 530679.jpg|thumb|upright|left|U.S. President [[Richard Nixon]] was an influence in the development of the Sidious character]]\nIn that film, the initial conception of Sidious was superseded by his depiction as a dictatorial ruler adept in the dark side of the Force. The Emperor was inspired by the villain [[Ming the Merciless]] from the ''[[Flash Gordon]]'' comic books.<ref>{{cite book|first=Dale|last=Pollock|title=Skywalking: The Life and Films of George Lucas|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=New York City|date=1999|page=142|isbn=978-0-306-80904-0}}</ref> The characterization of Sidious as an ambitious and ruthless politician dismantling a democratic republic to achieve supreme power is in part inspired by the real-world examples of [[Julius Caesar]], [[Napoleon Bonaparte]], and [[Adolf Hitler]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Nancy R.|last1=Reagin|first2=Janice|last2=Liedl|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Star_Wars_and_History.html?id=m81Bg4E_y_IC|title=Star Wars and History|publisher=[[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley]]|location=Hoboken, New Jersey|date=October 15, 2012|accessdate=August 30, 2013|isbn=9781118285251|pages=32, 144}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Star Wars: Attack of the Clones |url=http://www.time.com/time/covers/1101020429/story2.html|magazine=[[Time Magazine|Time]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|date=April 21, 2002|accessdate=December 13, 2009|quote=The people give their democracy to a dictator, whether it's [[Julius Caesar]] or [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon]] or [[Adolf Hitler]]. Ultimately, the general population goes along with the idea ... That's the issue I've been exploring: how did the Republic turn into the Empire?|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020605161308/http://www.time.com/time/covers/1101020429/story2.html|archivedate=June 5, 2002}}</ref> Other elements of the character come from [[Richard Nixon]].<ref>{{cite book|first=John C.|last=McDowell|title=The Gospel according to Star Wars: faith, hope, and the Force|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|location=Louisville, Kentucky|date=2007|isbn=978-1611648140|page=105}}</ref>{{efn|In his early drafts, Lucas used the plot point of a dictator staying in power with the support of the military. In his comment (made in the prequel trilogy era) Lucas attributed this to Nixon's supposed intention to defy the [[Twenty-second Amendment to the United States Constitution|22nd Amendment]],{{sfn|Kaminski|2008|p=95}} but the president was actually impeached and never ran for a third term. In the [[Star Wars: Episode II \u2013 Attack of the Clones (novel)|novelization of ''Attack of the Clones'']], it is noted that Palpatine had manipulated the law to stay in office as Supreme Chancellor for several years past his original term limit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/29/us/reagan-wants-end-of-two-term-limit.html|title=Reagan Wants End of Two-Term Limit|last=Molotsky|first=Irvin|date=November 29, 1987|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=New York Times Company|location=New York City}}</ref>}} Lucas said that Nixon's presidency \"got me to thinking historically about how do democracies get turned into dictatorships. Because the democracies aren't overthrown; they're given away.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark | last=Caro| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-05-18/features/0505180309_1_star-wars-sith-palpatine | title='Star Wars' inadvertently hits too close to U.S.'s role | newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] | publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Chicago, Illinois|date=May 18, 2005 | accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> Lucas also said, \"The whole point of the movies, the underlying element that makes the movies work, is that you, whether you go backwards or forwards, you start out in a democracy, and democracy turns into a dictatorship, and then the rebels make it back into a democracy.\"<ref>George Lucas, interview with Debbie Dykstra, at [http://www.scifi.com/sfw/issue421/interview.html SciFi.com]; last accessed August 17, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909135351/http://www.scifi.com/sfw/issue421/interview.html |date=September 9, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nLucas wanted to establish the Emperor as the true source of evil in ''Star Wars''. Screenwriter [[Lawrence Kasdan]] noted, \"My sense of the relationship between Darth Vader and the Emperor is that the Emperor is much more powerful ... and that Vader is very much intimidated by him. Vader has dignity, but the Emperor in ''Jedi'' really has all the power.\"<ref>Bouzereau, p. 265.</ref> He explained that the [[climax (narrative)|climax]] of the film is a confrontation between Darth Vader and his master. In the first scene that shows the Emperor, he arrives at the Death Star and is greeted by a host of [[Imperial stormtrooper|stormtroopers]], technicians, and other personnel. Lucas states he wanted it to look like the [[military parade]]s on \"[[May Day#International Workers' Day|May Day]] in [[Soviet Union|Russia]].\"<ref>George Lucas, commentary, ''Star Wars Episode VI: Return of the Jedi'', Special Edition (DVD, 20th Century Fox, 2004), disc 1.</ref>\n\nLucas fleshed out the Emperor in the prequel films. According to Lucas, Sidious' role in ''The Phantom Menace'' is to explain \"how Anakin Skywalker came to be Darth Sidious' apprentice\" and the events that led to his rise to power.<ref>{{cite book|first=Jonathan L.|last=Bowen|title=Anticipation: The Real Life Story of Star Wars: Episode I-The Phantom Menace|publisher=[[iUniverse]]|location=Lincoln, Nebraska|date=2005|page=4|isbn=978-0-595-34732-2}}</ref> According to film critic Jonathan L. Bowen, \"Debates raged on the [[Internet]] concerning the relationship between Darth Sidious and Senator Palpatine. Most fans believed the two characters are actually the same person with logic seeming to support their conclusion.\" Bowen notes that the debate was fueled by the fact that \"suspiciously Darth Sidious does not appear in the credits.\"<ref>Bowen, pages=93\u201394.</ref>\n\n[[File:August Labicana Massimo Inv56230.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Augustus]] in the robes and cloak of his position as ''[[Pontifex Maximus]]'']]\nIn ''Star Wars and History'' published by Lucasfilm, it describes Sidious' consolidation of power as being similar to the Roman political figure [[Augustus]]. Both legitimized authoritarian rule by saying that corruption in the Senate was hampering the powers of the head of state; both pressured the Senate to grant extraordinary powers to deal with a crisis, falsely claiming that they would rescind those powers once the crisis was over; and both relied on their strong control over military force.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Janice Liedl|editor2=Nancy R. Reagin|title=Star Wars and History|publisher=[[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley]]|location=[[Hoboken, New Jersey]]|date=2012|isbn=978-0470602003}}</ref>\n\n===Portrayal===\nWhen the Emperor first appeared in ''The Empire Strikes Back'', he was portrayed by [[Marjorie Eaton]] under heavy makeup.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alasdair|last=Wilkens|url=http://io9.com/5660319/yoda-was-originally-played-by-a-monkey-in-a-mask-and-other-secrets-of-the-empire-strikes-back|title=Yoda was originally played by a monkey in a mask, and other secrets of The Empire Strikes Back|website=[[i09]]|publisher=[[Univision Communications]]|location=New York City|date=October 10, 2010|accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref> [[Common chimpanzee|Chimpanzee]] eyes were superimposed into darkened eye sockets during post-production \"in order to create a truly unsettling image\". The character was voiced by [[Clive Revill]].<ref name=\"Darth SidiousBTS\">Sidious, Behind the Scenes, at the [http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/palpatine/?id=bts Star Wars Databank]; last accessed May 18, 2017. [https://web.archive.org/web/20061201010719/http://www.starwars.com/databank/character/palpatine/?id=bts Archived] December 1, 2006, at the [[Wayback Machine]].</ref> The makeup was sculpted by [[Phil Tippett]] and applied by [[Rick Baker (makeup artist)|Rick Baker]],<ref name=\"Hidalgo twitter\"/> who initially used his own wife, Elaine, for the makeup tests.<ref name=\"earwolf1\"/><ref>{{cite book|first=J.W. |last=Rinzler |title=The Making of Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-U0PAAAAQBAJ | isbn=9780345543363|publisher=[[Ballantine Group]]|edition=Enhanced |location=New York City|date=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n\"With [[Irvin Kershner|[director Irvin] Kershner]],\" Revill said, \"you had to keep the reins tight \u2014 you couldn't go overboard. It was the perfect example of the old adage 'less is more' \u2014 the Emperor doesn't say very much. But when he finally appears, it's at a point in the saga when everyone's waiting to see him. It's the Emperor, the arch villain of all time, and when he says there's a great disturbance in the Force, I mean, that's enough ''oomph''!\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Scott|last=Chernoff|url=http://www.wizardsandwarriors.org/show/articles/starwars.htm |title=Clive Revill: Voice of the Emperor|magazine=Star Wars Insider|publisher=[[Titan Magazines]]|date=May\u2013June 2000|issue=60 |location=London, England|accessdate=January 8, 2018|via=www.wizardsandwarriors.org}}</ref> Years later, during production of ''Revenge of the Sith'', Lucas decided to shoot new footage for ''The Empire Strikes Back'' to create [[Continuity (fiction)|continuity]] between the prequels and original trilogy. Thus, in the 2004 DVD release of ''The Empire Strikes Back'' Special Edition, the original version of the Emperor was replaced by [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[Shakespeare]]an actor [[Ian McDiarmid]], and the dialogue between the Emperor and Darth Vader was revised.<ref>{{cite news|first=Douglas|last=Hyde|title=Five major changes in the 'Star Wars' DVD|url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/Movies/09/20/star.changes/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting Systems]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date=September 23, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2006}}</ref>\n\nLucas and director [[Richard Marquand]] cast McDiarmid to play the Emperor for ''Return of the Jedi''. He was in his late 30s and had never played a leading role in a feature film, though he had made minor appearances in films like ''[[Dragonslayer (1981 film)|Dragonslayer]]'' (1981). After ''Return of the Jedi'', he resumed stage acting in [[London]].<ref name=\"ManofMystery\">{{cite web|title=Ian McDiarmid: Dark Force Rising|url=http://www.starwars.com/episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020124/index.html|website=StarWars.com|accessdate=August 17, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112153958/http://www.starwars.com/episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020124/index.html |archive-date=November 12, 2006 }}</ref> In an interview with ''BackStage'', McDiarmid revealed that he \"never had his sights set on a film career and never even auditioned for the role of Darth Sidious.\" He elaborated, \"I got called in for the interview after a ''Return of the Jedi'' casting director saw me perform in the [[Sam Shepard]] play ''Seduced'' at a studio theatre at the [[Royal Court Theatre|Royal Court]]. I was playing a dying [[Howard Hughes]].\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Simi|last=Horwitz|title=The Emperor's New Role|url=http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002577371|work=BackStage|publisher=Backstage, LLC|location=Los Angeles, California|date=May 25, 2006|accessdate=September 5, 2006}}</ref>\n\nMcDiarmid was surprised when Lucas approached him 16 years after ''Return of the Jedi'' to reprise the role of Darth Sidious. In an interview, he stated, \"When we were doing ''Return of the Jedi'' there was a rumor that George Lucas had nine films in his head, and he'd clearly just completed three of them.\" McDiarmid added, \"Someone said that, 'Oh, I think what he might do next is go back in time, and show how Vader came to be.' It never occurred to me in a million years that I would be involved in that, because I thought, 'oh well, then he'll get a much younger actor to play Sidious. That would be obvious.\" However, \"I was the right age, ironically, for the first prequel when it was made. ... So I was in the very strange and rather wonderful paradox of playing myself when young at my own age, having played myself previously when 100-and-I-don't-know-what.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Sidious Speaks|website=Homing Beacon|issue=134|date=April 14, 2005|url=http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/profile/beacon134.html|via=StarWars.com|accessdate=August 17, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112122327/http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/profile/beacon134.html |archive-date=November 12, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nSidious' role in the prequel films required McDiarmid to play two dimensions of the same character. Recalling the initial days of shooting ''The Phantom Menace'', McDiarmid stated, \"Stepping onto the set of ''Episode I'' for the first time was like going back in time, due to my experience in ''Jedi''. Sidious' an interesting character; he's conventional on the outside, but demonic on the inside \u2014 he's on the edge, trying to go beyond what's possible.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Actors and Characters - Part II: ''Star Wars'' Episode I: Production Notes|url=http://www.starwars.com/episode-i/bts/production/f19990501/indexp5.html|website=StarWars.com|accessdate=August 17, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060530063902/http://www.starwars.com/episode-i/bts/production/f19990501/indexp5.html |archive-date=May 30, 2006 }}</ref> McDiarmid added another layer to the character in ''Attack of the Clones''. He noted, \"[Darth Sidious] is a supreme actor. He has to be even more convincing than somebody who isn't behaving in a schizophrenic fashion, so he's extra charming, or extra professional \u2014 and for those who are looking for clues, that's almost where you can see them.\" McDiarmid illuminated on the scene where Padm\u00e9 Amidala is almost assassinated:\n\n{{quote|There's a moment in one scene of the new film where tears almost appear in his eye. These are [[crocodile tears]], but for all those in the movie, and perhaps watching the movie itself, they'll see he is apparently moved \u2014 and of course, he is. He can just do it. He can, as it were, turn it on. And I suppose for him, it's also a bit of a turn-on \u2014 the pure exercise of power is what he's all about. That's the only thing he's interested in and the only thing that can satisfy him \u2014 which makes him completely fascinating to play, because it is an evil soul. He is more evil than the [[devil]]. At least [[Satan]] fell \u2014 he has a history, and it's one of revenge.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Exercise of Power: Ian McDiarmid: Dark Force Rising|url=http://www.starwars.com/episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020124/indexp2.html|website=StarWars.com|date=January 24, 2002|accessdate=August 17, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061215043150/http://www.starwars.com/episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020124/indexp2.html |archive-date=December 15, 2006 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn ''Revenge of the Sith'', McDiarmid played a darker interpretation of the character. He explained that \"when you're playing a character of solid blackness, that in itself is very interesting, in the sense that you have no other motivation other than the accumulation of power. It's not so much about not having a moral center, it's just that the only thing that mattered is increasing power.\" He admitted, \"I've been trying to find a redeeming feature to Sidious, and the only one I've got so far is that he's clearly a patron of the arts because he goes to the [[opera]].\"<ref name=\"HB137\">\"Sidious' Point of View,\" in ''Homing Beacon'' 137, May 26, 2005, [http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/profile/beacon137.html StarWars.com]; last accessed August 17, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112122104/http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/profile/beacon137.html |date=November 12, 2006 }}</ref> McDiarmid compared the character to [[Iago]] from [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Othello]]'':\n\n{{quote|Everything he does is an act of pure hypocrisy, and that's interesting to play. I suppose it's rather like playing Iago. All the characters in the play \u2014 including [[Othello (character)|Othello]] until the end \u2014 think that \"Honest Iago\" is a decent guy doing his job, and he's quite liked. But at the same time there's a tremendous evil [[subconscious]] in operation.<ref name=\"ManofMystery\"/>}}\n\nMcDiarmid noticed that the script for ''Revenge of the Sith'' demanded more action from his character than in previous films. Lightsaber combat was a challenge to the 60-year-old actor, who, like his costars, took [[fencing]] lessons. The close-up shots and non-acrobatic sequences of the duel between Darth Sidious and Mace Windu were performed by McDiarmid.<ref>\"Becoming Sidious,\" Web Documentary, ''Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith'', Bonus Materials (DVD, 20th Century Fox, 2005), disc 2; also available at [http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/me3/18.html StarWars.com]; last accessed August 17, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060807013911/http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/me3/18.html |date=August 7, 2006 }}</ref> Advanced fencing and acrobatic stunts were executed by McDiarmid's doubles, Michael Byrne, Sebastian Dickins, and Bob Bowles.<ref>Cast and Crew of ''Revenge of the Sith'', at [http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/castcrew.html StarWars.com]; last accessed August 17, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060815190336/http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/castcrew.html |date=August 15, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nMcDiarmid's performance as Darth Sidious was generally well received by critics. [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' commented, \"Entertaining from start to finish and even enthralling at times, 'Sith' has some acting worth writing home about, specifically McDiarmid's dominant turn as the mastermind of the evil empire.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Todd|last=McCarthy|title=''Revenge of the Sith''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=May 5, 2005}}</ref>  Ed Halter of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' wrote that \"Ian McDiarmid's unctuous Emperor turns appropriately [[vampire|vampiric]] as he attempts to draw Anakin into the Sith fold with promises of eternal life.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Ed|last=Halter|title=May the Force Be Over; The end of the beginning: Lucas's adolescent space opera concludes in a CGI Sith Storm|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/film/0520,halter1,63970,20.html|work=[[The Village Voice]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|location=New York City|date=May 11, 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060628203757/http://www1.villagevoice.com/film/0520%2Chalter1%2C63970%2C20.html |archivedate=June 28, 2006|accessdate=August 17, 2006}}</ref> Still, his performance was not without detractors; [[David Edelstein]] of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' critiqued, \"McDiarmid isn't the subtlest of satanic tempters. With his lisp and his clammy little leer, he looks like an old queen keen on trading an aging butt-boy (Count Dooku) for fresh meat \u2014 which leaves Anakin looking more and more like a 15-watt bulb.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Edelstein|title=The Passion of the ''Sith'': I dream of Jedi|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2118604|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|publisher=[[The Slate Group]]|location=New York City|date=May 17, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2006}}</ref> McDiarmid had expressed interest in reprising the role of Sidious in the planned ''[[Star Wars: Underworld]]'' TV series,<ref>{{cite web|first=Eric|last=Goldman|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/08/24/ian-mcdiarmid-on-possibly-playing-the-emperor-in-the-live-action-star-wars-tv-series |title=Ian McDiarmid on Possibly Playing The Emperor in the Live-Action Star Wars TV Series |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[J2 Global]]|location=San Francisco, California|date=August 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> which remains un-produced, but according to [[Cory Barlog]], would have depicted the character as \"a sympathetic figure who was wronged by this fucking heartless woman. She's this hardcore gangster, and she just totally destroyed him as a person.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Moore |first=Trent |title=Aborted Star Wars Underworld TV series would've featured a 'sympathetic' Emperor Palpatine |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/aborted-star-wars-underworld-tv-series-wouldve-featured-sympathetic-emperor-palpatine |website=SyFy Wire |accessdate=September 21, 2019 |date=June 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 film ''The Rise of Skywalker'', the ninth episode in the [[Skywalker saga]], McDiarmid returned to the role of Darth Sidious on screen for the first time since ''Revenge of the Sith''. McDiarmid spoke of the process behind the Emperor's first scene in the film:\n\n{{quote|...the first thing I had to do \u2014 not everybody has a script \u2014 was when my voice was off screen, as Kylo Ren was coming into my lair. So I had this microphone that we called the \"God mic.\" Yes, it means it sounds like [[God]] and everyone can hear it in the recording studio in this vast soundstage. So everyone there heard my voice come back after all that time and it was a great moment.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>}}\n\nMcDiarmid was surprised to learn of the filmmakers' decision to bring back Sidious, given the character died in ''Return of the Jedi''.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/> The film's director, [[J. J. Abrams]], spoke of Sidious' inclusion in the [[Star Wars sequel trilogy|sequel trilogy]]: \"...when you look at this as nine chapters of a story, perhaps the weirder thing would be if the Emperor didn't return. You just look at what he talks about, who he is, how important he is, what the story is \u2014 strangely, his absence entirely from the third trilogy would be conspicuous\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/movies/jj-abrams-interview-the-rise-of-skywalker-star-wars/ |title=J.J. Abrams On ''The Rise Of Skywalker'' And The Return Of Darth Sidious (And, Yes, Maclunkey) |website=[[Uproxx]] |date=November 25, 2019 |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |first=Mike |last=Ryan}}</ref> On Sidious' portrayal in the film, McDiarmid said, \"he's fairly physically impaired, but his mind is as sharp as ever.\"<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>\n\n===Make-up and costumes===\n[[File:Star Wars and the Power of Costume July 2018 34 (Darth Sidious' Trade Federation robes from Episode III).jpg|thumb|Darth Sidious' robes from ''Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith'']]\n\nTransforming McDiarmid into the Emperor in ''Return of the Jedi'' required extensive makeup. McDiarmid remarked in an interview with ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'', \"Yes\u2014that was a four-hour job, initially, although we got it down to about two-and-a-half in the end. But this was just a little bit of [[latex]] here and there, a little bit of skin-scrunching.\"<ref name=\"ReturninEII\">{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020124/indexp3.html|title=Ian McDiarmid: Dark Force Rising|website=StarWars.com|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061215043157/http://www.starwars.com/episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020124/indexp3.html|date=December 15, 2006|archivedate=December 15, 2006|accessdate=April 24, 2019}}</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] wrote that the Emperor \"looks uncannily like [[Death (personification)|Death]] in ''[[The Seventh Seal]]'',\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Roger|last=Ebert|authorlink=Roger Ebert|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19970314/REVIEWS/703140303/1023|title=Return of the Jedi, Special Edition|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]|location=Chicago, Illinois|date=March 14, 1997|accessdate=August 17, 2006|via=rogerebert.com}}</ref> and film historian [[Robin Wood (critic)|Robin Wood]] compares him to [[Evil Queen (Disney)|the hag]] from ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'' (1937).<ref>{{cite book|first=Robin|last=Wood|title=Hollywood from Vietnam to Reagan...and Beyond: A Revised and Expanded Edition of the Classic Text|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|location=New York City|date=2003|page=[https://archive.org/details/hollywoodfromvie00robi/page/154 154]|isbn=978-0-231-12966-4|url=https://archive.org/details/hollywoodfromvie00robi/page/154}}</ref> McDiarmid remarked, \"When my face changes in [''Revenge of the Sith''], my mind went back to the early [[silent movie]] of ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1925 film)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'' with [[Lon Chaney]].\"<ref name=\"HB137\"/> Conversely, he required little makeup in ''The Phantom Menace'' and ''Attack of the Clones''. He recalled, \"I'm ... slightly aged [in ''AotC'']. In the last film, I had a fairly standard make-up on, but now, they're starting to crinkle my face.\"<ref name=\"ReturninEII\"/>\n\nSidious' wardrobe in the prequels, tailored by costume designer Trisha Biggar, played an important part in the development of the character. In ''Attack of the Clones'', explained McDiarmid, \"The costumes ... have got much more edge to them, I think, than the mere senator had in ''The Phantom Menace''. So we see the trappings of power.\"<ref name=\"ReturninEII\"/> On ''Revenge of the Sith'', McDiarmid said that \"To wear the costumes as the character I play is wonderfully empowering.\"<ref name=\"CraftinRevenge\">\"Crafting ''Revenge''\", in \"An Introduction to Episode III,\" at [http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/production/f20050518/indexp3.html StarWars.com]; last accessed August 17, 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051214182652/http://www.starwars.com/episode-iii/bts/production/f20050518/indexp3.html |date=December 14, 2005 }}</ref> McDiarmid's favorite costume in the film was a high-collared jacket that resembles [[snake]] or [[lizard]] skin. He stated that \"it just feels reptilian, which is exactly right for [Darth Sidious].\" According to Biggar, the character's costumes proved the most daunting challenge. She said, \"His six costumes get progressively darker and more ornately decorated throughout the movie. He wears greys and browns, almost going to black, taking him toward the dark side.\"<ref name=\"CraftinRevenge\"/>\n\nIn ''The Rise of Skywalker'', Sidious is unable to move without the aid of a large machine, to which he is attached.<ref name=\"Polygon Costume\"/> He is depicted as having eyes without pupils and rotting hands.<ref name=\"Polygon Costume\"/> Costume designer [[Michael Kaplan (costume designer)|Michael Kaplan]] opted to dress the Emperor in a utilitarian black robe, which he wears for the majority of the film.<ref name=\"THR Costume\">{{cite magazine |first=Stephanie|last=Sporn |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/how-michael-kaplan-costumed-700-creatures-rise-skywalker-1264308 |title=How Michael Kaplan Costumed 700 Creatures in ''The Rise of Skywalker'' |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=December 20, 2019 |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the film, the Emperor rejuvenates himself using the Force and becomes physically mobile.<ref name=\"Polygon Costume\"/> He dons a new costume \u2014 a formal robe with red velvet \u2014 which Kaplan refers to as \"his true Emperor's garb\".<ref name=\"THR Costume\"/>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n<!-- ATTENTION! Please keep this section brief. Every mention of Darth Sidious in popular culture does not need to appear here. -->\nWith the premiere of ''Return of the Jedi'' and the prequel films and the accompanying merchandising campaign, Sidious became an icon in American [[popular culture]]. [[Kenner Products|Kenner]]/[[Hasbro]] produced and marketed a series of action figures of the character from 1983 to 2005.<ref>{{cite book|first=Geoffrey T.|last=Carlton|title=Star Wars Super Collector's Wish Book: Identification & Values|publisher=Collector Books|location=Paducah, Kentucky|date=2003|isbn=978-1-57432-334-4}}</ref> According to [[John Shelton Lawrence]] and Robert Jewett, \"These action figures allow children ('4 & up') to handle the symbols of the Force.\"<ref name=\"American Superhero\">{{cite book|first1=John|last1=Shelton Lawrence|first2=Robert|last2=Jewett|title=The Myth of the American Superhero|publisher=[[Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing]]|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|date=2002|page=[https://archive.org/details/mythofamericansu00lawr_0/page/266 266]|isbn=978-0-8028-4911-3|url=https://archive.org/details/mythofamericansu00lawr_0/page/266}}</ref>\n\nAcademics have debated the relationship of Sidious to modern culture. Religion scholars Ross Shepard Kraemer, William Cassidy, and Susan Schwartz compare Sidious and ''Star Wars'' heroes to the [[theology|theological]] concept of [[Dualistic cosmology#Moral dualism|dualism]]. They insist, \"One can certainly picture the evil emperor in ''Star Wars'' as [[Satan]], complete with his infernal powers, leading his faceless minions such as his red-robed Imperial Guards.\"<ref>{{cite book|first1=Ross|last1=Shepard Kraemer|first2=William|last2=Cassidy|first3=Susan|last3=Schwartz|title=Religions of Star Trek|publisher=[[Westview Press]]|location=Boulder, Colorado|date=2003|page=69|isbn=978-0-8133-4115-6}}</ref> Lawrence and Jewett argue that Vader killing Sidious in ''Return of the Jedi'' represented \"the permanent subduing of evil\".<ref name=\"American Superhero\"/>\n\nSince ''Return of the Jedi'' and the prequel films, Sidious' name has been invoked as a caricature in politics. A ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' editorial noted that anti-[[Pork barrel|pork]] [[blog]]gers were caricaturing [[West Virginia]] Senator [[Robert Byrd]] as \"the Emperor Palpatine of pork\", with Senator [[Ted Stevens]] of [[Alaska]] having \"clear aspirations to be his Darth Vader.\" The charge followed a report that linked a [[secret hold]] on the [[Federal Funding Accountability and Transparency Act of 2006]] to the two senators.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/opinion/283392_secreted.html|title=Open Government: Pork protection|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|location=Seattle, Washington|date=September 1, 2006|accessdate=September 5, 2006}}</ref> Politicians have made comparisons as well. In 2005, [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democratic]] Senator [[Frank Lautenberg]] of [[New Jersey]] compared [[U.S. Republican Party|Republican]] [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Majority Leader]] [[Bill Frist]] of [[Tennessee]] to Sidious in a speech on the Senate floor, complete with a visual aid.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alec|last=Russell|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1490425/Star-Wars-jibe-in-US-Senate-battle-of-the-filibuster.html|title=Star Wars jibe in US Senate battle of the filibuster|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|location=London, England|date=20 May 2005|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nA [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]] editorial stated \"no cultural icon can exist without someone trying to stuff it into a political ideology. The ''Star Wars'' saga, the greatest [[popular culture|pop culture icon]] of the last three decades, is no exception... the Emperor's dissolution of the Senate in favor of imperial rule has been compared to Julius Caesar's marginalization of the [[Roman Senate]], Hitler's power-grab as [[Chancellor of Germany (German Reich)|chancellor]], and [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|FDR's]] [[Judiciary Reorganization Bill of 1937|court-packing scheme]] and creation of the [[Imperial Presidency|imperial presidency]].\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Thomas A.|last=Firey|title=Star Wars Saga Reflects Political Ideals|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,157229,00.html|website=[[Fox News]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corp]]|location=New York City|date=May 22, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===On the Internet===\n\nAfter Disney's purchase of [[Lucasfilm]] in 2012 and the [[Star Wars Sequel Trilogy|sequel trilogy]]'s success in the mid-late 2010s, the character became the subject of various [[internet meme]]s, emphasizing certain lines of dialogue the character spoke in ''[[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/darth-plagueis-palpatine-senate-meme/|title=Suddenly, Star Wars' Darth Sidious has conquered the entire meme landscape|author=Hathaway, Jay (January 27, 2017)|publisher=[[Daily Dot]]|access-date=April 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://melmagazine.com/en-us/story/the-reddit-group-dedicated-to-making-memes-about-the-star-wars-prequels|title=The Reddit Group Dedicated to Making Memes About the 'Star Wars' Prequels|author=McDermott, John|publisher=[[Mel Magazine]]|access-date=April 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/mg49gx/reddit-is-engaged-in-a-highly-entertaining-star-wars-meme-war|title=Reddit Is Engaged in a Highly Entertaining 'Star Wars' Meme War|author=Koebler, Jason (March 14, 2017)|publisher=[[Vice (magazine)|Motherboard (website)]]|access-date=April 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Works cited'''\n* {{cite book | title = The Secret History of Star Wars | last = Kaminski | first = Michael | year = 2008 | origyear = 2007 | publisher = Legacy Books Press | isbn = 978-0-9784652-3-0 | ref = harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* Anderson, Kevin J., and Daniel Wallace. ''The Essential Chronology''. New York: Del Rey, 2000. {{ISBN|0-345-43439-0}}.\n* Bortolin, Matthew. ''[[The Dharma of Star Wars]]''. Somerville, Mass.: Wisdom Publications, 2005. {{ISBN|0-86171-497-0}}.\n* Feeney, Mark. ''Nixon at the Movies: A Book about Belief''. Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 2004. {{ISBN|0-226-23968-3}}.\n* Hanson, Michael J., and Max S. Kay. ''Star Wars: The New Myth''. Philadelphia: Xlibris, 2002. {{ISBN|1-4010-3989-8}}.\n* Horne, Michael Allen. ''[[Dark Empire Sourcebook]]''. Honesdale, Penn.: West End Games, 1993. {{ISBN|0-87431-194-2}}.\n* Jensen, Hans, and Richard Chasemore. ''Star Wars: Complete Locations''. New York: DK Publishing, 2005. {{ISBN|0-7566-1419-8}}.\n* Luceno, James. ''Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith: The Visual Dictionary''. New York: DK Publishing, 2005. {{ISBN|0-7566-1128-8}}.\n* Lyden, John. \"The Apocalyptic Cosmology of ''Star Wars''.\" ''Journal of Religion and Film'' 4 (No. 1, April 2000): [https://web.archive.org/web/20070721074055/http://www.unomaha.edu/jrf/LydenStWars.htm online].\n* Pe\u00f1a, Abel G. \"Evil Never Dies: The Sith Dynasties.\" ''Star Wars Insider'' 88 (June 2006).\n* Reynolds, David West. ''Episode I: The Visual Dictionary'' New York: DK Publishing, 1999. {{ISBN|0-7894-4701-0}}.\n* Reynolds, David West. ''Star Wars: Attack of the Clones: The Visual Dictionary''. New York: 